		<div class="row">
			<p class="posted">By Medicine Hat News on February 13, 2019.</p>
			
			<div class="subscribeNow">
			<a  class="subscribeNow" href="/forms/subscribe/subscribe.php">SUBSCRIBE NOW</a>				
			</div>
			<div class="alignright"><img src="https://medicinehatnews.com/wp-content/uploads/Cubs-300x268.jpg" class="attachment-medium size-medium wp-post-image" alt="" srcset="https://medicinehatnews.com/wp-content/uploads/Cubs-300x268.jpg 300w, https://medicinehatnews.com/wp-content/uploads/Cubs-280x250.jpg 280w, https://medicinehatnews.com/wp-content/uploads/Cubs.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></div><p>Brett Vanderveer had a pretty great birthday Tuesday night.</p>
<p>The Medicine Hat Cubs goaltender stopped all 31 shots fired his way as the junior B team beat the Wheatland Kings 2-0 on the road in Strathmore, taking the opening game of their best-of-three Heritage League playoff series.</p>
<p>The Cubs got goals from Noah Irvine and Tristan Stensrud in the second period, then hung on in the third.</p>
<p>Vanderveer, 19, played in 32 of the Cubs&#8217; 38 regular season games and will likely start Game 2 Thursday night, 7:45 p.m. at the Kinplex. Medicine Hat doesn&#8217;t have home ice advantage in the series and will look to advance to play top seed Coaldale in the second round.</p>
<p>Shots were 37-31 Cubs.</p>
